          "body": "Verses 13-28 constitute one of the most concentrated wealth catalogues in the Old Testament — 666 talents of gold annually (9:13), 200 large shields at 600 shekels each (9:15), 300 smaller shields at 300 shekels each (9:16), an ivory throne overlaid with pure gold flanked by fourteen lions (9:17-19), all drinking vessels of gold and silver accounted as nothing (9:20), triennial voyages to Tarshish returning with gold, silver, ivory, apes, and peacocks (9:21). The Chronicler does not present this as mere biography. Read against the Deuteronomic blessing theology of Deuteronomy 28:1-14, the catalogue is covenant confirmation in material form: 'the LORD will make you abound in prosperity... all peoples of the earth shall see that you are called by the name of the LORD' (Deuteronomy 28:11-12). The nations bringing tribute to Solomon (9:23-24) is the historical instantiation of Psalm 72:10-11: 'Let the kings of Tarshish and of the islands bring presents; the kings of Sheba and Seba offer gifts.' The Chronicler invites his post-exilic readers — with their modest temple and no king — to see this as precedent and promise: the pattern is real; the covenant is not dead."
